A Constitution with the Brezhstange in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi .
Egypt , in terms of constitutional declaration , which temporarily grants him unlimited powers , more than ever , has decided to put everything on a map .
On Wednesday , he announced on Wednesday that the constitutional assembly will be adopting its final version on Wednesday .
Just a week ago , the Head of State granted two additional months to complete his work .
Egypt has , for almost two years , now been building a temporary , multi-pronged text , which weakens institutional stability and leads to a legal breakthrough .
This new initiative has only made it more divided .
For his opponents , the president stubbornly withstood his &quot; autocratic delirium &quot; by continuing to &quot; break his word &quot; and &quot; the right to go &quot;
On the part of its supporters , it is assured that it is a way to stop the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and accelerate the transition process
A referendum should be held in 14 days .
A very short period that forces the brothers to abandon their intentions to explain the text of the section for section .
It is also a way for the President to rediscover its public and democratic legitimacy , while the protests are raging throughout the country .
After confirming in an interview with the American weekly newspaper , Mohamed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote favourably .
So , with this rebellion on an overwhelming vote , the Egyptian people are being asked to take an ultimatum : &apos; I do not agree with my draft or I keep the full power , &quot; the latter should be called upon to end the Constitution .
85 mostly Islamist members of this constitutional assembly yesterday adopted the text in a strange atmosphere .
The majority of Liberals did not meet the call .
Shortly before the constitutional declaration in November , they turned out to be abused , because they felt they were unable to assert their views .
Human rights organisations , religious minorities and civil society have acted equally .
In the wake of the decision , the 11 people , deputy members , were added yesterday .
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly approved unanimously .
The commentators , however , were entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day ... the time for prayer was expressed , because some members of the panel felt that the Pendelu ’ s Pendel was not exactly the same .
The text which was passed last night is based on 234 articles .
Article 2 , which draws attention to all of them , remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that &apos; the principles of Sharia are the main source of justice &apos; .
The Salafist parties , which are an important demand for the establishment of Islamic law , had hoped to replace &apos; the principles &apos; by &apos; the rules &apos; , which would have made it possible to apply a more rigorous application
For the Islamists , the fact that this article has not been changed proves to be a proof of its good will and respect for the other members of Egyptian society .
&quot; hypocrisy &quot; trusts the liberals , who are only seen as propaganda .
For they are told that the constitution is being Islamised by other articles
They are in particular in Article 220 , which recognises the University of Al-Azhar an advisory function , particularly in relation to the review of conformity with the laws of Sharia .
According to the Egypt-German student , Sophie Pommier , this is worrying , because the people who are asked to give opinions have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy .
One can see the first signs of a theocracy .
Liberals are also worried about the fact that the next Rector of this university will be far less moderate than the current one .
&quot; At present , there is no concrete religious commitment .
This Constitution is a constitution that we are maintaining .
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema , but academics , who are trained in the French system , are invited to the city of Alexis Blouet , who writes a thesis on Egyptian constitutional order .
However , he acknowledges that there can be a ambiguity in Article 220 , as the concepts used are opposed to the religious vocabulary .
The first is the &quot; Fiqh &quot; &#91; Islamic jurisdiction , Anm . Red , &#93; .
And in the future , the question of how civil judges are competent to decide on this issue could be raised .
In addition to its religious aspect , the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers that it grants to the President of the Republic
The Muslim Brothers argue that they are significantly reduced compared with the former regime .
Another point of conflict : the powers of the army
In line with the military &apos;s wish , the review of the defence budget will not be presented to Parliament , but to a national defence council .
There will also be no ban on civil trials in military courts , as the associations of defence of human rights have demanded .
The latter also share their concerns about the text they consider to be a freedom of liberties .
The blasphemy of blasphemy is maintained , and insults are now banned , which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression , especially for the press .
