&quot; The great and powerful &quot; leads to Moscow : migrants save money for language .
While Members and civil society are discussing the usefulness of the law on compulsory language tests for migrants , criminals are already carrying out counterfeiting certificates .
Every year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow , Saint Petersburg and other cities of Russia .
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia : Uzbekistan , Tajikistan and Turkmenistan .
Their only aim is to earn money to keep families remaining in their homeland .
On 1 December , a law in force , which stipulates that each working class must be a test , must be certified by the Russian language .
This regulation is currently only for migrants , who want to work in the services sector , in the local housing sector and in retail markets
However , the tests under the Federal Ministry of Migration should be compulsory in future for all host workers .
We must not only be testing language tests , but also testing and the bases of legislation .
Language skills must be proven both for the preservation and renewal of the work permit .
Exceptions are only valid for citizens of countries in which Russian is a language
This law also exempts people who have received their training certificates and diplomas before the USSR in 1991 .
The Right , Problems and Protection of Rights
The entire test centre will be held under the aegis of the Puschkin Institute of Russian Language , Russian University of Ukraine , Moscow State University , the Sankt Petersburger Staats-Universität and other Russian universities .
Migrants can leave the tests in all cities ; already more than 160 centres in Russia have already opened up .
The initiative to introduce the tests has been supported by the representatives of the State Duma and the Federal Ministry of Migration
On the other hand , civil rights activists asked about the law in the press several times : what is the whole thing
What changes do the rules need to have to show language skills , both for the Russians and for the host workers ?
Above all , the Minister for Migration , who has chosen to be responsible , is to reduce the number of forced workers .
&quot; Many are now talking about the protection of workers &apos; rights &quot; , says the head of the Federation &apos;s representative of the Transatlantic Migration Authority in Tajikistan , Viktor Sebelew
However , their rights must be protected before their departure .
Only organised recruitment will solve 90 % of the problems of foreign workers .
Migrants encounter migrants without a profession , education , language skills and medical care .
