NKU ’ s head : control of the black system is unavoidable by debt
The Czech Republic has good control bodies and adequate laws , but it falls short of its application .
In the interview for Update álně.cz , this is the Vice President of the High Control Office ( Nejvyšší Controllní úřad , NKÝ ) , Miloslav Kala
&quot; A law is never perfect , but it must be properly applied - and this is not the case with us , &quot; says Kala the current situation .
A similar result appears to be shared by Czech and German auditors .
In his practical practical example , he is conducting the appointment of Prime Minister Petr Nečas on the so-called &apos; Black &apos; system .
Recently , the Prime Minister said that ODS would not harden entrepreneurs with inspections , so the system is now banned or allowed ?
&quot; A law must have its validity , and if there is a law , then it is not just the President of the Government , the authority of the police , whose duty to control compliance with the law is to be obstructed in its activities , &quot; says Kala .
At the meeting of the Committee on Budgetary Control , you spoke about a joint Czech project , which compared the laws of both countries with regard to public contracts .
What was the issue here ?
This is a parallel test which we started about two years ago .
In short , it is about the European legislative system to determine how public contracts are to be handled , that is to say , the national legislation , and , finally , the actual application is the right one .
We are not yet in a position to deal with this issue , but we are not yet in a position to compare ourselves with it .
It confirms that it is not enough to constantly create new and more precise rules , and that we must also deal with the actual application of the law .
How can the project help you to help you , what is the result of this project ?
This joint control could help us to constantly try to achieve a perfect system of legislation and to reduce and suspend thresholds , if this is not a very positive thing .
Economics means being a thing at a reasonable price ( which not always is the lowest price ) and excluding illegal enrichment or even criminal activity .
But reducing the cost of contracts does not guarantee that we achieve this goal .
Perhaps it is even so that we are putting the system on a purely excessive &apos; paper tape &apos; , and those who are looking for the loopholes in the system are much easier to exploit the system than when the thresholds are higher .
You are talking about the problems in the practical implementation of the Czech Public Prosecutor .
How does the control system work in Germany ?
Is there a similar authority such as our NKPP , or does the system work differently
As regards the authorities , the German counterparts are the German equivalent of the Federal Institute of Technology , which is similar to us and also has a college , which is only a slightly different form , but in principle both institutions are working .
The competences are also comparable to that of Germany , but Germany is a federal state , so that these audit hoses also exist in the individual states - this is the German system of ours .
The BRH must only be able to control the federal funds which are equivalent to our government funds
Public funds are administered by the district and municipalities , subject to control of the national customs authorities .
With regard to German legislation , is it easier than ours ?
I would like to say that , although it is not entirely true , it is not a good example , but it is often referred to as an example , but it certainly cannot be said that Germany is better off .
Can that be because the auditors are better off ?
This certainly does not , but as I said , I like such comparisons .
