PTA has been involved in the development of the highly successful meteorological missiles ( Rakieta Meteorologiczna ) , the first Polish rocket for scientific research since 1956 .
The first type , the RM-1 , was completed in 1957 , the first started on October 10 , 1958 .
The missiles with a maximum flight of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and woke not 5 kg .
Later , an improved version , RM-1A , was built , and in 1959 Błędów-Wrath started flying flight tests with the two-stage RM-2 .
The missiles were 1,4 m long and about 11,5 kg .
Another development level should be able to provide true scientific work - the Rakete RM-34 should reach a flying height of up to 14.5 km and be used to monitor altitude .
In 1962 , however , the further development was suspended
The first racket of type RM was developed in 1962 by Meteor 1 missiles .
The missiles were designed as two-stage rails , their total length was 510 cm and the starter was 32.5 kg .
Three types of these missiles were developed ( Meteor-1A , -1B and -1C ) , which differ in size for scientific instruments .
The Meteor 1A rockets had a transport space with 0.4 litres , meteor1B over 0.34 litres and meteor1C over 0.62 litres .
The maximum escape was 37 km .
In 1965 to 1968 , the Meteor 2 missiles were developed in the aeroplanes , which started their first flight tests in October 1970
Meteor 2 had a start-weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a load of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km .
The versions were then built in Meteor-2H and Meteor 3
