The lifting of the law on non-profit work is not a solution
Last week the Constitutional Court suspended the law on non-profit work .
This decision has made a lively debate in public .
It is certainly interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective .
The liberal economic systems in the EU and in the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition .
In the end , it means that the individual economies are interacting with each other in a permanent conflict
This is the principle of free trade and the free , unlimited movement of private capital , which is handful of financial speculation .
Due to the large differences in the value of work ( wages ) , prices are rising .
This concept is a situation where manufacturers try to compete with commercial competition by importing cheaper goods by using competition , thereby increasing the share of the market and increasing its profits .
Most companies , for their part , are doing so to buy their production abroad , or to buy it out there , or to spend their business , the result is high unemployment in countries with comparable labor costs .
Since private capital does not have social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it generates , it necessarily increases government spending .
This situation is being reinforced by the fact that entrepreneurs are absolutely unwilling to pay their taxes and to replace the social and social damage caused by them .
This situation is generally known , so that there are no specific statistics on this matter .
The rudimentary practice of private capital is a situation in which governments are forced to compete in competition with competing countries to reduce the social level of their own people artificially and thus to attract foreign capital to the country .
In other words , governments provide private capital without regard to social consequences .
This is especially true in changes in legislation .
The aim of these measures is to force their own people to accept the dictates of private capital , especially in the area of wages .
This is due to economic constraint in long-term unemployment , and to the reduction of workers &apos; rights .
The result is growing poverty , as well as ever greater differences between rich and poor
