Szabo : &quot; Deutsche must play more role &quot;
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine .
According to Stephen Szabo , an expert for US relations , Berlin is balancing a narrow diplomatic degree .
German wave : At the beginning of the week Germany first signalled that it would vote against the request for observer status by the Palestinians to the United Nations
Then , however , Berlin remained .
Why ?
Stephen Szabo : Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza .
Now , however , Germany must be cautious about its particular relationship with Israel
But at the same time , I believe that it does not support American positions
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel .
During the reign in Libya in March 2011 , Germany also abstained in the vote on establishing a no-fly zone .
After all , it was ratified by NATO
Does Germany have a clear position on important international issues ?
Yes , that is true .
This is because it is precisely its foreign policy that is moving away from a policy which has been managed by the United States , and which has been managed by the United States .
It is a great deal to add that Europeans do not have a coherent and coherent policy
So the Germans are being confronted between the fronts .
They are expected to play a more independent role , but they are not accustomed to doing so .
I think they are still in the same position , but they are on the road to a &apos; normal &apos; foreign policy .
A foreign policy , such as France or Great Britain
What does a &apos; normal &apos; foreign policy mean , specifically from a German perspective
It shows the readiness to take positions on national interests , which are independent of both the US and European partners .
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy , namely exports and its relations with certain regions , such as Russia , China and the Middle East .
Germany ’ s economic interests are different to a certain degree other than those of other big powers , and Germany must protect its interests
Did these economic interests have influence over the Middle East conflict and the UN vote ?
Firstly , Germany has large market markets in the Middle East , especially in the Gulf States .
It must be cautious , however , to be careful , not to mention the elixir , but also the elites .
This is certainly a matter of course .
But I would not be too much weight to attach to that , which is not a completely unilateral relationship .
But it is certainly a major role in German considerations .
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by abstaining on important decisions , such as when it voted on Palestine ?
I believe that there is broad understanding in Europe and even in the United States .
This is why I do not believe that this is a dramatic break , as in the Libyan question .
Perhaps Germany will even be taking some respect for this .
It is clear that it is a serious matter for international players to be taken seriously and to be considered to be interested
There are various opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative .
The US , on the other hand , has clearly voted against
Are there differences between the US and many European nations ?
American domestic politics always exists .
I believe that the Obama administration has a very good understanding of the European position .
But , given the political situation , the government is not , of course , able to stand
I believe that the actual differences of opinion are not as big as they are always .
If you look at relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu , Obama is not so bright about Netanyahu ’ s policy .
Does it not have a hard time to agree to its close relations with Israel and the US on one hand and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other
I believe that this is so difficult for the Germans .
It would , of course , be a little simpler for the Germans if there had been a coherent and united European policy , which is not currently the case
So they cannot be part of a broader line , and instead must move things forward from their own position .
They are doing so with the euro .
In future , I believe that Germany will have a leading role to play a European position .
That is not just for Germany , for the relationship with Israel .
This has always been a sensitive subject .
But I believe that the Germans are clear that they must play a more independent role .
Does Germany itself have a role as an important international player , and Germany is going to be taking a major role
Or does Germany still have a hard job ?
Germany is not yet used to it , it is still unpleasant and , for obvious reasons , it is still difficult to play a bigger role .
For example , when we look at the euro crisis , every time Germany takes a bigger role , various anti-German sentiment are free .
This makes it not easy for the Germans .
This is actually the old problem : you are not going to be swept away by hostile countries .
Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US .
It must be a good neighbour for many neighbours and opinions , and that is not easy
Now the US &apos;s influence is constantly being taken up in European politics , but the EU is not filling this vacuum , who will stay ?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role
Even if they don &apos;t like them , they are unpleasant and make them even more unpopular - c &apos; est la vie !
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington , an institute in which academic and political experts from Europe and North America are working together on the challenges of the transatlantic community .
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund , where he specializes in German politics , US foreign policy and transatlantic relations .
