We knew that the government had tried to do a lot , such as the marketing of parades with pheromons or the organisation of speed-date ends ( fast flirts ) .
May I say that many of these ideas were creative , but they did not make a success .
So we thought : why do we not make a lot of creative use to deal with this problem , such as a rap ?
1.2
The government of Singapore is not easy to take this issue .
Every year , it has USD 1.300 for political measures to encourage citizens to get more children .
A package of government and family members grants up to $ 15,000 per child , extending maternity leave and distributive benefits .
But everything has not been successful yet .
Singapore is a rich , high-tech city in the southeast of Asia , which is also known for its conservative and strict social control .
According to its national national population , the birth rate is currently at 1.2 children per woman .
The last time this rate was over 2 - which is also known as an implementation rate - was in 1976 .
So why are the Singapore not getting more children ?
Tan Wei Ming , director of the national and family policy of the national population , says that this is due to a &quot; better education &quot; and &quot; greater career opportunities &quot; .
&quot; This has enabled people to marry out and to form a family to form far more options in terms of life goals and set priorities &quot; , she explains .
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the higher number of individuals and to the relinquishing of marriage and birth , which is a result of a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore .
Meanwhile , an immigration policy aimed at a drastic increase in migration to counter the population &apos;s poverty has led to a resurgence of the local population .
In Singapore , there are websites where hardly crazy Xenophobia is blowing against many new migrants , especially against the Chinese , who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating .
Immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the governing party in Singapore has reached its worst election result since independence last year .
Since the elections , an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and taxes for foreign workers .
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in birth rates has the familiar effects on a nation &apos;s economic growth , tax revenues , health costs and immigration policy , the example of Singapore shows unexpected consequences .
The government is trying to ensure that not many small apartments are built .
This has already had an impact on the housing market .
The Agency for Urban Development has started to control the number of small apartments known as &apos; shoe boxes &apos; and can be built in certain areas of the city .
These apartments have a living area of 46 square metres and show a great success .
However , there is concern that they can promote the life of the single entity and that they discourage the bystanders from building large housing for families .
But Lim Yew Soon , General Director of the EL Developers estate company , says that his &quot; shoe boxes &quot; are selling much faster than larger residential units .
They are so popular , and the units are sold more quickly , day and even weeks , than larger residential units .
This means that they are much better for our Cash Flow .
However , it is true that the new standards give developers clearer guidelines , which previously put obstacles in the way of building too many small residential units within a project .
Too much
Singapore is a city state .
Even if these new rules could lead to an increase in national fertility rates , talks with the Singapore countries working in the financial district are bound to be seen to have no major impact .
&quot; The people are strong , the apartments and also the education are expensive , so it is excited by many people &quot; says a young manager .
Children can get others .
&quot; It is important to me to have my own money and time &quot; says another , about twenty years old man .
Men and women are leading their careers , the stress and the costs of property and education as reasons for not having children .
So the Singapore has the last word when it comes to getting children - the government can do so much .
